Monthly Summary – February 2026

In February 2026, my work focused on five key areas: (1) ML-driven rule construction for the Loans Broker low-Delphi segment, (2) B&Q target segment tightening investigation, (3) INIT process troubleshooting and monitoring, (4) development of the Apple Risk Framework, and (5) ongoing enhancement and positioning of the Rule Engine framework. Alongside these priorities, I also supported complaints handling, responded to ad-hoc analytical requests, and progressed continuous professional development activities.

A significant proportion of the month was dedicated to constructing and refining machine learning–driven rules for the Loans Broker low-Delphi group. This project involved iterative feature selection, rule construction, performance evaluation, and governance alignment. Using an AI-supported approach, I applied structured feature screening and optimisation techniques to identify high-impact variables and translate model outputs into implementable rule bands. Particular focus was placed on ensuring that the generated rules were both performance-driven and operationally practical within existing decisioning constraints.

The proposed rule set was finalised and prepared for presentation to the Risk Committee (RC). The paper was successfully delivered at the RC meeting and received positive feedback, with approval granted for progression. One of the key advancements during this project was the strengthening of the Rule Engine’s AI capability through the integration of built-in explainability techniques (XAI). By embedding explainability directly into the feature selection and rule construction workflow, the Rule Engine further evolved into a genuinely AI-driven decision optimisation framework while remaining governance-ready and transparent. This enhancement improves both analytical robustness and stakeholder confidence in the outputs.

The B&Q target segment tightening project represented another substantial rule construction initiative this month. Unlike standard rule build exercises, this project incorporated an additional proxy validation section and a machine learning modelling component focused on product-type analysis. The objective was not only to identify potential tightening opportunities but also to assess segment-level behaviour more holistically through modelling insights. Initial baseline results were obtained, and early directional findings have been established. Due to time constraints and prioritisation of the Broker low-Delphi RC submission, the project is scheduled for further refinement and completion ahead of next month’s RC cycle, with a formal paper being prepared for submission.

In parallel, considerable time was spent troubleshooting and stabilising the new version of the INIT processes. This involved identifying inconsistencies, resolving technical issues, and ensuring that process outputs aligned with business expectations. Although key issues have been addressed, continued monitoring will be required over the coming months to ensure the new version operates smoothly without operational disruption. Establishing process stability is critical to maintaining data integrity and supporting downstream analytical work.

Work also commenced on the Apple Risk Framework this month. The initial structure has been developed, with several components confirmed and a small number of items pending clarification. A revised Excel version of the framework will be generated to reflect the updated structure and ensure consistency across reporting and governance documentation. This framework aims to formalise risk segmentation and oversight in a structured and scalable way.

Additionally, discussions were held regarding current concerns within the loan Risk-Based Pricing (RBP) model. Key issues were reviewed, and potential next steps were outlined. Given competing priorities, this item remains under consideration and will be progressed further once capacity allows. The discussion, however, provided useful alignment on potential solution directions and highlighted areas requiring future analytical deep dives.

Beyond these strategic initiatives, I continued to support complaint investigations and ad-hoc analytical requests as they arose. These activities ensure ongoing business support and responsiveness to emerging issues, while maintaining alignment with broader risk strategy objectives.

From a capability development perspective, my Continuous Professional Development (CPD) hours now stand at 7.5 hours for the year to date. This includes ongoing learning in AI-driven optimisation methods and governance-oriented analytical design, supporting the continued evolution of the Rule Engine and related decisioning frameworks
